Write-up: Matt's team is absolutely dominating 😏🍆. Alvin Kamara is putting up numbers like he’s got something to prove 💦🍑, and Justin Jefferson? Let’s just say he’s catching balls like they’re invitations to something much more intimate 😈🔥. Courtland Sutton even found the end zone despite Bo Nix’s lackluster performance 🍑🍆. But the real story here is Matt’s full-frontal assault on the league 🍆💦💪. His team is fisting opponents with precision and stamina 👊💦🍑🍆, and it’s been extremely satisfying for Matt 😏🔥—and maybe a little painful for his opponents 🥵💦.

Calvin made a bold move trading for Brian Thomas Jr., and it already paid dividends this week as Thomas had a monster game. Derrick Henry continues to bulldoze through defenses like they’re a bunch of middle schoolers at a JV game, and with DK Metcalf lighting it up, Calvin’s team is the equivalent of getting that rare double-decker ice cream cone—you don’t know how he’s balancing it all, but you can’t stop watching.

Nick’s team is cruising, but much like Drake’s discography, there’s a sense of déjà vu. Sure, Ja’Marr Chase is pulling in elite stats, but you can’t help but feel like you’ve seen this before—big starts, lots of hype, but what about the endgame? Nick’s team might be "If You’re Reading This It’s Too Late" levels of smooth right now, but he needs to prove it’s not all hype. Drake albums come and go, but only time will tell if Nick’s team has staying power.

Minh put up 124.53 points this week, so maybe the “pretender” narrative needs to be put on ice. Nico Collins is out here making secondaries look foolish, and while the rest of the roster isn’t exactly scaring anyone, Minh is still putting up Ws. At 4-0, it’s time to stop pretending Minh is just coasting on luck—he’s here to win, even if no one knows how.

Team Name: The Nabers think im sellin dope
Write-up: Aaron is back, baby! After a rough start to the season, Aaron pulled out a win this week, and his squad is starting to look like the "good ol’ days" version of his team. Zamir White is putting in work, and Aaron’s roster is showing signs of life. He might be trending upward like your stock portfolio when you don’t check it for six months and then surprise—it’s up! Stay tuned, folks.

Karan’s squad is holding steady, but the question remains: when is he going to make the move for a top-tier wide receiver? With Cooper Kupp still out, Karan has the assets to trade for a game-changer. Time to take some risks or risk fading into mediocrity. But hey, at least his RBs are still doing the heavy lifting.

John’s team had a solid week thanks to Geno Smith and Jahmyr Gibbs. Geno is back on the map with a performance that reminded everyone why he’s no longer just a backup, and Gibbs is starting to show signs of life. With Swift still doing his thing, John’s team is flying under the radar, quietly preparing to take over when everyone’s least expecting it. The Bloodline is coming for the throne, just you wait.

Kendall’s team is in rough shape. Pacheco’s injury has left a massive hole in the roster, and Kendall’s recent pickups have been about as useful as a paper towel in a rainstorm. DeVonta Smith and Tank Dell being out didn’t help either, making last week a Toy Story 3-esque tearjerker. Woody and Buzz would be proud of the effort, but Sid’s mutant toys are running the show now, and it's not looking good.

Prashant took a heavy loss this week, and it wasn’t pretty. Joe Mixon and Dak Prescott failed to carry the team, and it’s starting to look like the wheels might be coming off the Woodshed express. Prashant is going to need a serious rebound to avoid getting buried in the standings. This week was less of a woodshed and more of a lumberyard—lots of potential, but nothing getting built.

Anthony’s team is slipping on more banana peels than Donkey Kong in Mario Kart. Tyreek Hill is supposed to be the blue shell of this lineup, but lately, he's been playing more like a green shell—useful but not devastating. It’s like Anthony’s team has been hit by a banana peel right as he was about to cross the finish line, sending him spinning into the wall while watching his competitors zoom by. Time to rev up the engines again!

Rohan’s team is making more desperate calls than Drake in Marvin's Room, except this time, it’s to the waiver wire. Patrick Mahomes is running out of downfield options, and Travis Etienne’s shoulder injury isn’t helping the cause. Rohan needs to make some moves, or his team will keep leaving him on read. Hopefully, his dating life is a little better than this.

Henry’s team continues to chug along, and Josh Jacobs and Kenneth Walker are leading the way like they’re pulling a sled through the snow. The rest of the roster isn’t doing much, but when you’ve got two strong legs like that, you don’t need the flashy extras. Henry just needs a little more out of the rest of the roster before he can start getting real wins.

Zack’s team is floundering, but if anyone knows how to hang in there, it’s Smitty Werbenjagermanjensen—he was No. 1, after all. Unfortunately, right now, Zack’s team is looking more like the Flying Dutchman’s crew, doomed to wander the bottom of the standings in a haunted ship of despair. At least there’s still time for a comeback. Just need to find that magic No. 1 hat.

Alfred lost a heartbreaker by 0.4 points, and that’s got to sting. CeeDee Lamb is starting to heat up, and Travis Kelce’s connection with Taylor Swift (wait, we meant Patrick Mahomes) is only getting better. Alfred’s team is on the brink of turning it around, but he needs just a little more from the rest of the squad if he wants to avoid these painful close calls. Maybe a little Tay-Tay magic will help?

Team Name: Master Has Given Dobbins A Sock
Write-up: Joey’s squad is still searching for some consistency. Michael Pittman finally showed up, but Joe Burrow is still looking like he's playing on a sprained calf—probably because he is. If Joey’s going to turn this ship around, it’s going to take more than one good week from Pittman. Dobby’s still looking for his sock, and Joey’s team is still looking for its mojo.

O heavenly fantasy gods, we humbly ask for your mercy upon Holy Bible. Grant Tee Higgins the strength to reach the end zone, and let George Pickens deliver consistent points for Shaun's team. We pray for Nick Chubb’s swift healing and return, so that he may lead Holy Bible to victory. Bless Shaun with a miracle of points this week, as we faithfully await thy favor. In the name of touchdowns and triumph, we pray. Amen.
